{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/eating-disorders/background-information/causes/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"754dd31e-b289-5e87-a9a4-ffc837631dcd","slug":"causes","fullItemName":"Causes","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 78e9efcf-cb2f-42bb-a515-49a6e78f431e --><h2>What are the causes?</h2><!-- end field 78e9efcf-cb2f-42bb-a515-49a6e78f431e -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 4c831dd1-2c22-443f-a086-b2ea18dc4a4c --><!-- begin field 91edca5a-cdf4-4c95-9d88-feaddc4c211b --><ul><li><strong>The aetiology of eating disorders is not fully understood </strong>but is generally considered to involve a combination of genetic, neurobiological, and sociocultural factors.</li><li><strong>Factors associated with development and maintenance of an eating disorder include:</strong><ul><li><strong>General factors</strong> such as female sex, adolescence and early adulthood, and being overweight as a child.<ul><li>About 90% of people with an eating disorder are female.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Neurobiological factors:</strong><ul><li>Eating disorders have been associated with abnormal neurotransmitter activity (including serotonin and dopamine) and satiety-related hormones (including adiponectin and ghrelin).</li><li>It is not known if these are involved in the development of an eating disorder or are the result of physiological alterations due to malnutrition.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Psychosocial factors such as:</strong><ul><li>Anxiety, depression, perfectionism, low self-esteem, body dissatisfaction and overestimation of body size.</li><li>Societal idealizations about body shape including professional or recreational pressure to be slim (for example dancing, modelling, and athletics).</li><li>Household stress, social isolation and poor social support.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Family history of an eating disorder, psychiatric disorder or substance misuse:</strong><ul><li>The risk of developing an eating disorder has been reported as 7-12 times higher in people with a family history.</li><li>Results from twin studies are conflicting — some show a strong correlation (for example estimated heritability of anorexia nervosa 33–84% and bulimia nervosa 28–83%) while others show no correlation.</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/eating-disorders/references/\">Campbell, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/eating-disorders/references/\">Hay, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/eating-disorders/references/\">Bould, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/eating-disorders/references/\">Lock, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/eating-disorders/references/\">Zipfel, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/eating-disorders/references/\">Keski-Rahkonen, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/eating-disorders/references/\">Montano, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/eating-disorders/references/\">Bould, 2017a</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/eating-disorders/references/\">BMJ Best Practice, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/eating-disorders/references/\">NICE, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/eating-disorders/references/\">Royal College of Psychiatrists, 2019</a>]</p><!-- end field 91edca5a-cdf4-4c95-9d88-feaddc4c211b --><!-- end item 4c831dd1-2c22-443f-a086-b2ea18dc4a4c -->","topic":{"id":"dee69261-4638-5eba-bd8b-fac36f0849f3","topicId":"c8280f80-020a-4f11-9951-a37624b9aa55","topicName":"Eating disorders","slug":"eating-disorders","lastRevised":"Last revis